Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

A sales forecast is a prediction of future sales revenue based on historical data, industry trends, and the status of the current sales pipeline. Businesses use the sales forecast to estimate weekly, monthly, quarterly, and annual sales totals. A company needs to make an accurate sales forecast as it adds value across an organization and helps the different verticals to chalk out their future course of action.

Forecasting helps an organization plan its sales operations by region and provides valuable insights to the supply chain team regarding the procurement of goods and materials. An accurate sales forecast process has many benefits which include improved decision-making about the future and reduction of sales pipeline and forecast risks. Moreover, it helps to reduce the time spent in planning territory coverage and establish benchmarks that can be used to assess trends in the future.

Objective¶

SuperKart is a retail chain operating supermarkets and food marts across various tier cities, offering a wide range of products. To optimize its inventory management and make informed decisions around regional sales strategies, SuperKart wants to accurately forecast the sales revenue of its outlets for the upcoming quarter.

To operationalize these insights at scale, the company has partnered with a data science firm—not just to build a predictive model based on historical sales data, but to develop and deploy a robust forecasting solution that can be integrated into SuperKart’s decision-making systems and used across its network of stores.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of the various products and stores.The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • Product_Id - unique identifier of each product, each identifier having two letters at the beginning followed by a number.
  • Product_Weight - weight of each product
  • Product_Sugar_Content - sugar content of each product like low sugar, regular and no sugar
  • Product_Allocated_Area - ratio of the allocated display area of each product to the total display area of all the products in a store
  • Product_Type - broad category for each product like meat, snack foods, hard drinks, dairy, canned, soft drinks, health and hygiene, baking goods, bread, breakfast, frozen foods, fruits and vegetables, household, seafood, starchy foods, others
  • Product_MRP - maximum retail price of each product
  • Store_Id - unique identifier of each store
  • Store_Establishment_Year - year in which the store was established
  • Store_Size - size of the store depending on sq. feet like high, medium and low
  • Store_Location_City_Type - type of city in which the store is located like Tier 1, Tier 2 and Tier 3. Tier 1 consists of cities where the standard of living is comparatively higher than its Tier 2 and Tier 3 counterparts.
  • Store_Type - type of store depending on the products that are being sold there like Departmental Store, Supermarket Type 1, Supermarket Type 2 and Food Mart
  • Product_Store_Sales_Total - total revenue generated by the sale of that particular product in that particular store

# function to create labeled barplots
def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=9)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().sort_values(ascending=False).index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

Observations:

  • Dataset consists of 8763 rows and 12 features.

  • There are no NULL, NA or Duplicated values in given SuperKart dataset.

  • Product ID:

    • Field is having unique values and dataset has total 8763 products.
  • Product Sugar Content:
    • There are 3 unique values and clean-up is required.
    • Data seems to be imbalanced with 55% of data is associated with "Low Sugar" and remaining 45% with with other 3.
  • Product Type:
    • There are total 16 Unique product types.
    • Need to analyze the sales distribution across the product types to identify if we have to keep the 16 product types or group those into fewer products.
  • Store Size:
    • There are 3 different store sizes in dataset.
  • Store ID:
    • There are only 4 unique store id's suggesting 4 stores.
    • More than 50% of products to be from one store, suggesting class inbalance.
    • OUT004 is showing as Medium Store, however it has large number of products.
    • Other three stores have almost 15% each of remaining products.
  • Store loc City Type:
    • Data is mostly having Tire2 city types.
  • Store Type:
    • There are 4 unique store types and 50% of data belongs to Supermarket Type2.
  • Store_Establishment_Year:
    • As this year is not related to sales and products and as we already have store id, we can check further if we have to keep this feature for model development.

  • Product_Weight:

    • As dataset metadata does not include product weight units, For simplicity we can assume weight is in lb's.
    • Product weight ranges from 4LB to 22LB, with 50% of products are in range of 12LB and 75% falls under 14LB.
    • From respective box plot we can observer, there are outliers in the data.
    • From histogram plot, though it seems to have a distribution closer to uniform distribution, but if we closely observe, it doesn't show a single prominant peak and relatively flat peaks accross the range of weights. Rather it has some variations in frequency across different weight ranges.

  • Product_Allocated_Area:

    • Box plot shows there is right skewness of products allocated larger space compared to products allocated to lower space range.
    • This strong skewness suggest we need to consider transformation of data for model building.
    • Need to further check Sales with respect to space allocated.

  • Product_MRP:

    • As we do not have product MRP units, we can Assume US "\$ - USD" as unit value.
    • Products range from \$31 to \$266 with average cost at \$146.7
    • Mean and Median are very close to each other if not same.
    • There are only few outliers 31 upperbound and 26 lowerbound.
    • Product can be clustered based on their price range.

  • Product_Store_Sales_Total:

    • Histogram shows the total sales having right skewed distribution.
    • This indicates larger number of products produced lower total sales, were as fewer products producted higher total sales.
    • Sales values range from Minimum of \$33 to \$8000
    • Box plot clearly shows the significant number (82) of outliers on the higher end of the sales distribution and 37 products outside the lower end.

Model Building¶

Given the scope of the project is to have a model to predict "Sales Forecast", and considering non linear relationship between target and predictive variables. To obtain better performance and accuracy I am selecting below two models for model development from the given models.

  • Random Forest
  • XGBoost

Define functions for Model Evaluation¶

In [18]:
# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, model_name, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Model Name:" : model_name,
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

The ML models to be built can be any two out of the following:

  1. Decision Tree
  2. Bagging
  3. Random Forest
  4. AdaBoost
  5. Gradient Boosting
  6. XGBoost

Observations¶

  • As we initially observed "Random Forest" and "XGBoost" default models are having higher RMSE and MAE compared to fine tuned models and less less R-Squared and Adj. R-Squared.

  • In addition to this, we can see difference between Training and Test sets are higher indicating overfitting on training data.

  • Comparing tunned models:

    • "RF Tuned Model" is having low RMSE and MAE compared to "XGB Tuned Model",indicating better prediction accuracy.
    • "R-Squared" and "Adj. R-Squared" for Random Forest model is having little higher "XGBoost" model. indicating model explains more of the variance in target variable.
    • MAPE is slightly lower in 'Random Forest' tunned model. Indicating slightly smaller average percentage error in predictions.

  • Comparing Overfitting:

    • By comparing the difference between Training and Test performance of tuned models, we can observe XGB Tuned model is having lower difference from training to test set compared to Random Forest tunned model scores difference, indicating XGB Tunned Model is having slightly lower overfitting on training data compared to Random Forest.

  • Given the objective is to predict forecast sales on on seen data, model that generlizes better on unseen data is better and also XGB Tunned Model performance scores difference is also low compared to it's Random Forest model.

Hence selecting tunned "XGBoost Tunned Model" to be better choice for final forecast model

%%writefile backend_files/app.py

#importing necessary libraries
import numpy as np
import joblib
import pandas as pd
from flask import Flask, request, jsonify
from flask_cors import CORS # Import CORS

# Initialize Flask application
sk_sf_api = Flask("SuperKart Sales Forecast Predictor")
CORS(sk_sf_api) # Enable CORS for all routes

# Load the model
model = joblib.load("SuperKart_sales_forecast_model.joblib")

# Rout for homepage (GET Request)
@sk_sf_api.get("/")
def home():
    """
    This function handles GET request to the root URL of the API.
    It returns a welcome message.
    """
    return "Welcome to SuperKart Sales Forecast Predictor!"

# Endpoint for Single product sales prediction (POST Request)
@sk_sf_api.route("/v1/predict-single", methods=["POST"])
def predict_sales_forecast_single():
    """
    This function handles POST request to the /predict-single URL.
    It takes input data in JSON format containing store and product details and return
    predicted sales forecast as a JSON response.
    """

    # Get the JSON data from the request body
    data = request.get_json()

    # Create a dictionary with all expected columns, including dummy IDs
    sample = {
        'Product_Id': 'dummy_product_id', # Dummy value
        'Product_Weight':       data['Product_Weight'],
        'Product_Sugar_Content': data['Product_Sugar_Content'],
        'Product_Allocated_Area':data['Product_Allocated_Area'],
        'Product_Type': data['Product_Type'],
        'Product_MRP': data['Product_MRP'],
        'Store_Id': 'dummy_store_id',     # Dummy value
        'Store_Establishment_Year': data['Store_Establishment_Year'],
        'Store_Size': data['Store_Size'],
        'Store_Location_City_Type': data['Store_Location_City_Type'],
        'Store_Type': data['Store_Type']
    }

    # Convert extracted data into dataframe
    input_data = pd.DataFrame([sample])

    # Make predictions using the loaded model
    prediced_sales_forecast_log = model.predict(input_data)[0]

    # Calculate actual forecast
    prediced_sales_forecast = round(float(np.expm1(prediced_sales_forecast_log)), 2) # Use expm1

    # Return the actual predicted forecast
    return jsonify({"Predicted Sales Forecast (in dollars)": prediced_sales_forecast})

# Endpoint for batch prediction
@sk_sf_api.post("/v1/predict-batch")
def predict_sales_forecast_batch():
    """
    This function handles POST request to the /predict-batch URL.
    It takes input data in CSV file format containing store and product details and return
    predicted sales forecast as a JSON response.
    """

    # Get the file from input request
    file = request.files["file"]

    # Read the CSV file into a DataFrame
    input_data = pd.read_csv(file)

    # Define the expected columns in the order they were in the training data (X_train.columns)
    expected_columns = ['Product_Id', 'Product_Weight', 'Product_Sugar_Content',
                        'Product_Allocated_Area', 'Product_Type', 'Product_MRP', 'Store_Id',
                        'Store_Establishment_Year', 'Store_Size', 'Store_Location_City_Type',
                        'Store_Type']


    # Check if 'Product_Id' and 'Store_Id' columns exist, if not, add them
    if 'Product_Id' not in input_data.columns:
        # Insert 'Product_Id' column at the correct position with a dummy value
        # Find the index where 'Product_Id' should be based on expected_columns
        prod_id_idx = expected_columns.index('Product_Id')
        input_data.insert(prod_id_idx, 'Product_Id', 'dummy_product_id')

    if 'Store_Id' not in input_data.columns:
         # Insert 'Store_Id' column at the correct position with a dummy value
         # Find the index where 'Store_Id' should be based on expected_columns
        store_id_idx = expected_columns.index('Store_Id')
        input_data.insert(store_id_idx, 'Store_Id', 'dummy_store_id')


    # Ensure the columns are in the correct order for the pipeline
    # This step is crucial if the uploaded CSV might have columns in a different order
    input_data = input_data[expected_columns]


    # Make predictions for all requested products & Stores
    predicted_sales_forecast_log = model.predict(input_data)

    # Convert log-transformed predictions back to original scale
    predicted_sales_forecast = np.expm1(predicted_sales_forecast_log).round(2)

    # Add predictions to the DataFrame
    input_data['Predicted_Sales_Forecast'] = predicted_sales_forecast

    # Return the DataFrame with predictions as a JSON response
    return jsonify(input_data.to_dict(orient='records'))

# To run the Flask app (for testing in a local environment or specific deployment setups)
if __name__ == "__main__":
  sk_sf_api.run(debug=True) # Turn off debug=True in production

import streamlit as st
import requests
import pandas as pd

# Defining function to reset the app to initialization stage.
def reset():
    st.session_state.name = ''

# Set title for the streamlit APP
st.title("SuperKart Sales Forecast Predictor")

# creating a list of values in the app for user selection.
prod_type_lov = ["Fruits and Vegetables", "Snack Foods",  "Frozen Foods", "Dairy", "Household", "Baking Goods", "Canned", "Health and Hygiene", "Meat", "Soft Drinks", "Breads", "Hard Drinks", "Others", "Starchy Foods", "Breakfast", "Seafood"]
Product_Sugar_Content_lov = ["Low Sugar", "Regular", "No Sugar"]
store_type_lov = ["Departmental Store", "Food Mart", "Supermarket Type1", "Supermarket Type2"]
store_loc_city_type_lov = ["Tier 1", "Tier 2", "Tier 3"]
store_sze_lov = ["Small", "Medium", "High"]


# Section for subheader
st.subheader("Enter Product Details:")

# Collect user inputs
Product_Type = st.selectbox("Product Type:", prod_type_lov)
Product_Sugar_Content = st.selectbox("Product Sugar Content:", Product_Sugar_Content_lov)
Product_Weight = st.number_input("Product Weight (in kg):", min_value=0.0, step=0.1, value = 11.0 )
Product_MRP = st.number_input("Product MRP (in dollars):", min_value=10.0, value = 150.0 )
Product_Allocated_Area = st.number_input("Area Allocated in store for product:", min_value = 0.004, max_value = 0.4, value = 0.09)

st.subheader("Enter Store Details:")

# Collect user inputs

Store_Type = st.selectbox("Store Type:", store_type_lov)
Store_Establishment_Year = st.number_input("Store Established Year:", min_value=1900,step = 1, value = 2000)
Store_Size = st.selectbox("Store Size:", store_sze_lov)
Store_Location_City_Type = st.selectbox("Store Location City Type:", store_loc_city_type_lov)

# Convert user input into dataframe
input_data = pd.DataFrame([{
    'Product_Weight':  Product_Weight,
    'Product_Sugar_Content': Product_Sugar_Content,
    'Product_Allocated_Area': Product_Allocated_Area,
    'Product_Type': Product_Type,
    'Product_MRP': Product_MRP,
    'Store_Establishment_Year': Store_Establishment_Year,
    'Store_Size': Store_Size,
    'Store_Location_City_Type':  Store_Location_City_Type,
    'Store_Type': Store_Type
}])

# Make pridiction when "predict" button is clicked.
if st.button("Predict"):
  response = requests.post("https://Bobby734-SuperKart-SalesForecast-Predictor-Backend.hf.space/v1/predict-single", json=input_data.to_dict(orient='records')[0])

  if response.status_code == 200:
    result = response.json()
    st.success(f"Predicted Sales Forecast: {result['Predicted Sales Forecast (in dollars)']}")
  else:
    st.error(f"Error: {response.status_code}")
    st.error(f"Error: {response.text}")
    st.error(f"Error: {response.content}")
    st.error(f"Error: {response.headers}")
    st.error(f"Error: {response.request}")

# Selection for batch pridiction
st.subheader("Batch Pridiction")

# User selection to upload file
uploaded_file = st.file_uploader("Upload a CSV file", type=["csv"])

# Make pridiction when "predict" button is clicked.
if st.button("Batch Predict"):
  if uploaded_file is not None:
    files = {'file': uploaded_file}
    response = requests.post("https://Bobby734-SuperKart-SalesForecast-Predictor-Backend.hf.space/v1/predict-batch", files=files)
    if response.status_code == 200:
      result = response.json()
      st.success("Prediction Complete!")
      st.dataframe(pd.DataFrame(result))
      # write the prediction to file and allow to download
      df = pd.DataFrame(result)
      df.to_csv('prediction.csv', index=False)
      st.download_button("Download Predictions", data=open('prediction.csv', 'rb').read(), file_name='prediction.csv', mime='text/csv')
    else:
      st.error(f"Error: {response.status_code}")
      st.error(f"Error: {response.text}")
      st.error(f"Error: {response.content}")
      st.error(f"Error: {response.headers}")
      st.error(f"Error: {response.request}")
  else:
    st.warning("Please upload a CSV file.")

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

Actionable Insights:

  • Model leverages key features like "Product MRP", "Product Weight", "Product Allocated Area", "Store Type", "Store Location City Type" and "Store Established Year" to forecast sales.

  • Among above listed, "Product MRP", "Product Weight", "Store Type" and "Product Type" were significant factors influencing the sales.

  • While the model provides good overall predictions, variations across different stores still contribute to some prediction error.

  • The developed backend API allows both single product/store forecast and batch prediction forecast visa CSV upload. This enables API to be scallable and automated.

  • Frontend WebApp provides an intuitive user interface for store managers or planners to easily input details and see forecast.

Business Recommendations:

  • Integrate the API with inventory management to optimize product stock levels and availability accross stores.
  • Targeted sales with respect to products, stores and citys based on respective sales forecast.
  • Capture additional store level detils and other store information to improve model performance.
  • Monitor Models performance using new sales data, compare actual sales vs predict sales.
  • Setup alerts for significant deviation from predictions.
  • Perform phased rollout and collect feedback on performance and usability both front end and back end.
  • Based on user feedback, enhance front end and include any additional factos impacting sales and models performance.
